
Great â€” if you want the whole project to compile with Java 8, you must do two things:

â¸»

âœ… STEP 1 â€” Make Maven use Java 8 to compile

Add this to your parent POM (recommended) OR to every module POM:

<properties>
    <maven.compiler.source>1.8</maven.compiler.source>
    <maven.compiler.target>1.8</maven.compiler.target>
    <maven.compiler.release>8</maven.compiler.release>
</properties>

Or using plugin config:

<build>
    <plugins>
        <plugin>
            <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
            <artifactId>maven-compiler-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>3.11.0</version>
            <configuration>
                <source>1.8</source>
                <target>1.8</target>
                <release>8</release>
            </configuration>
        </plugin>
    </plugins>
</build>

Without this, your parent POM still forces Java 17, and you will always get:

invalid target release: 17


â¸»

âœ… STEP 2 â€” Remove Java 17 flags from IntelliJ

Make sure your Maven runs with Java 8:

In IntelliJ:

File â†’ Settings â†’ Build Tools â†’ Maven â†’ Runner
â†’ Set JRE to Java 8

File â†’ Settings â†’ Build Tools â†’ Maven â†’ Importing
â†’ Set â€œJDK for importerâ€ to Java 8

Now verify:

Run:

mvn -version

Expected:

Java version: 1.8.0_xxx

If it still shows Java 17 â†’ Maven is not using the correct JDK.

â¸»

âœ… STEP 3 â€” Remove Java 9+ options (they break Java 8)

Anywhere you have:

--add-exports ...

DELETE IT
Java 8 does not support this option.

â¸»

âš ï¸ Final Note

Some dependencies in your project may require Java â‰¥ 11 (e.g., some Hibernate, some Aspose, some Jackson versions).

If after forcing Java 8 you see errors like:

Unsupported major.minor version 55.0

It means a library is compiled with Java 11+ and cannot run on Java 8.

But first, set the compiler to Java 8 and ensure Maven runs on Java 8 â€” letâ€™s get that part stable.

